annotation: My friend who hasn't played chess for a while decided not to play ...c5 is usual response so this was new territory for us.
g6 is more common and so I was thinking of play a Botvinnik type formation but with this I decided to look for a d4 break.
Planning Ne2 O-O and d4
My friend plays this to stop my d4 break. However at first I thought this was a blunder.
This is where the complications will begin. I expected Nc5 however blacks move is interesting.

!? Black plays e4 protecting the knight however there are some complications: Nxe4 (Nxe5? Qxd3 is what my friend played to start with however I let him take it back) Nxe4 Bxe4 Nc5 Qc2 Bxe4 (Or Qxe4) and black is better due to a safer king however he is a pawn down but I beleive he has compensation. White's weak king and light squares as well as some troublesome development of the DSB. So maybe rather than Bxe4 white Plays Qxe3 Nf6 with pressure on the d-pawn. White can play e4 or Nc3 but not Nf4 due to g5 and kicking the Knight and dropping the d-pawn. This is probably better for white (I like Nc3) because he has two pawns for his bad king however he needs to exchange pieces and get to an endgame to make advantage of this.
White is pressuring the q-side threatening mate. Now Black played Rd7 to start with however Bh3 pins the rook and wins the exchange so my friend took it back.
Wanting to play Bb5 to kick the DSB or jump into c6.
I prefer a6 however This is ok.
Threatening Qxd4
To start with my opponent played Kb8 then I played Nc6+ and he resigned (we were nearly out of time) however he then saw he could have played Kb7 but we were out of time so we didn't continue.
However now I will try and analyse this. All comments welcome.
My favorite opening the King's Pawn Play.
He responds with the Nimovitz defense but I do not see this too often.

I usually consider this ? as it is pushing a pawn.  However this was ! because it forces the knight to retreat.  That is because the knight can become dangerous in this position since it has a potential to attack powerful pieces based on my AP analysis.
I do not know why he made that move instead of Ng8 because he is not going to castle.

I chose that candidate because his knight is becoming more powerful in this position.  However this move was ? because I brought my queen out way too early.  Therefore Bd3 would have been better as it would have also chased the knight away.
I do not why he made this move.
I respond by placing him in check immediately and this was based on my KKQ assessment.  However this move was ?.
That is because I just wasted a move since he is threatening to capture my queen with cxb5.
Therefore I am now forced to retreat my queen.
He chose this candidate to force an exchange and that will work when 6.exf6 exf6 are played.
This gives me a tactical advantage because his queen is now blocked.
He made this move to free his queen.
I chose this candidate based on my KKQ assessment.  If I had left my queen on d3 he would have played Nc5 and threatened to capture my queen with Nxd3.  I did not want to deal with that threat.
I do not why he made this move but this will benefit me.
That is because I used an AP assessment to play a powerful fork between his knight and queen.
In this position he was forced to retreat his queen so I will be ahead by two points.  That is because his knight will be exchanged for my pawn when 10.fxe4 dxe4 are played.

I decided to bring out one of my knights based on the AP assessment.  That is because I am now threatening to capture his free e pawn with Nxe4 in this position.  If this happens he will not be able to recapture my knight with Qxe4 or he will loose the queen because I will respond with Qxe4.
As a result he is now threatening to capture my queen with Bxe3.
Therefore I am forced to retreat my queen.  In exchange I now threaten to capture his free g pawn.
Consequently he is now forced to protect his g pawn and his rook.
I chose this candidate because it will force an exchange and attack his queen after the exchange when exd3 followed by Bxd3 are played.  This was also based on my AP assessment.
As a result he protects his queen by placing me in check.
However that does not bother me because I simply respond by bringing out my other knight.
I do not know why made this move because I was not going to place him in check due to his h pawn.
If I did not move my a pawn he would have been able to pin my knight on c3 and I did not want that to happen.  This threat was also based on my AP assessment.
He chose this candidate because he wants to capture my queen on g3.

I could have played Qh3 and forced a queen exchanged with Qxh3 followed by gxh3 but I did not want do that because I would then have two h pawns.  I felt that it would put me at a structural disadvantage because my rooks would not connected here.  Therefore I respond by retreating my queen and it was 
! in my opinion.  In fact I think that this was my best candidate move based on the potential KKQ and AP in this position.
I do not know why he made that move but "a knight on the rim is grim" in general.
Based on my KKQ and AP analysis I decided to place him in check because it is serious instead of a mere nuisance in this position.  That is because I will win his free g pawn after he moves his king.
Now he is forced to move his king.
This is the free pawn that I had mentioned earlier.

I do not know why chose that candidate because his rook was already protected by the queen.  In other words I could not have played Qf6.  However that does not bother because I will capture his f pawn based on the AP when Bxf4 is played.  In addition he cannot recapture the DSB or he will loose his queen and get placed in check because I will respond with Qxf4+.
He made this move because he wants to capture my queen with hxg5 but I am not about to let that happen.
Instead I respond by placing him in check based on my KKQ and possible AP.
That is because he is now forced to move there or I will win his rook for free because I will play Qxh8 in this position.
Therefore I assess another KKQ by placing him in check with my bishop.

He also could have played Kh8 but it does not matter where he moves because I now have an inevitable mating pattern against him and will successfully capture his queen in this position.  How did I reach this conclusion?  With my KKQ analysis.
He cannot recapture his queen.  Therefore he can play Kg8 or Kh7 but it does not matter at this point.
That is because I will immediately force a mate with Qg7#.

I learned about the KKQ and AP assessments from a chess mentor.  This mentor also told me that it is only important to worry about "serious checks" not "nuisance checks" when analyzing the KKQ.  I am using these assessments more frequently and it is helping me to become better at chess.
Here my opponent begins by pushing up his rook. Yes his rook. Your eyes are really getting bad aren't they?
I counterattack by using my bishop. (Just kidding! Its actually my knight!)
This early mistake here will cost my enemy dearly. Taking his knight out early increases the chance of a left-mate-pin also commonly known as 'fmoodle-smong'.
Here I have set up the 'donkey formation' a subtle but overhwelming opening in its own right. Few can defend against its brutal simplicity.
Another silly mistake here. Just silly. Silly silly silly.
Here you can see the potential of triple-check. Checkity.
A fluid beautifully timed move. The pentagonal formation created by the bishop-hook is unmistakable.
A fork! (Or maybe a spoon I'm not quite sure...)
Here white plays very badly... a rookie mistake that has ensured his own brutal demise.

I learnt three things from this move:

1. Noodles are yummy. 2. I can't count.
Another mistake here. A meaningless tactic that will accomplish nothing.
Bwa ha ha ha ha ha ha ha *snort* ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha! (also a spork)
You can see here how novice my opponent is. Imbecilic and featherbrained moves like these only serve to accentuate his inane and immaturity. It also opens up the right flank-fmoddle. Or something.
Another silly mistake utterly useless- oh wait its checkmate. No matter.
I always move to e5 by force.
e6 blocks the c8 bishop moving on to the diagonal.
Normal structure but the knight blocks the black bishop even more
I can make that can't I?
?? It reamins leaving the king queen and the other two bishops stuck. One check could easily do it. Bb4 would have been a whole lot better
Developing
Hmmm...
Preparing to castle
Bxg5 also pins the knight on e7.
Oops you've made a terrible mistake!! A very easy-looking blunder...
A tool for not looking properly
Not too good looking!
Takes en passant! I could be wealthy now!!
Black has made a serious mistake which involves losing his queen.
See what I mean?
And white remains a queen and rook ahead and including pawns 15 points ahed. White will easily win after that pawn sacrifice.
But now the bishop pins my knight. I don't want to end up with a doubled pawn....
....so I move Qd2
Aha to chase the bishop away.
Oh.
Mmmf. The bishop on b4 is under attack.
And the bishop returns.
Good.
Just as I expected.
Now my bishop can move! So Rc8 will be no help at all for Black!
Chasing the knight away.
So..?
Lookin' good.
I don't think a rook for a bishop in this situation might be a very good idea.
Good thing the knight's popped away and even better he's blocked the rook so at least I can do waht I planned.
Qg6+
Knight's on the rim are dim but I just wanted to resit trying. Anyway I'm 17 points up.
And the knight couldn't move because Qxg8 was checkmate so much better from now on
Attacking the bishop.
So he moves but not to a very good square though
Here's what I mean.
Easy as a pie and the game is won with me being 20 points up.
I am annotating this game for a few key learning elements.  Although I wound up winning the game both allanshessw and I made several mistakes that warrant further investigation.
Ruy Lopez (Spanish opening)
All fairly standard Ruy Lopez so far.  Black has several options here to move the game forward.  The most common play here is to bring the knight out at Nf6.
Shoring up the e pawn and giving his bishop more options for development a solid move.
Discretion being the better part of valor I protect my king to allow my rook to eventually get into the game on the e file.

This move is logical and will give Black's bishop some good options.  g6 as an alternative is not very sound in my opinion.  I would have played Nf6 in this position most likely but no fault anywhere yet.

In recent games I have taken to attacking the center early and often.  I like creating opportunities and you need to attack to do that.  This move allows my dark-squared bishop entrance into the game and also attacks the center. Moves that can accomplish more than one thing are always best.

An alternative could have seen Black take with the knight (Nxd4) instead of this move.  The logical conclusion to that series would be
8.	Nxd4	exd4
9.	Bd5	Rb8
10.	Qxd4	

By taking here I now have an opportunity.  There is now no longer a pawn in front of his king.  My main goal now is to get my own e pawn out of the way so I can directly challenge his king.
Now I move to bring my plan into effect.  Black has two potential responses here and only one of them is worth considering.
This move is basically forced.  Had black chosen Bd7 Nxd4 will cause some problems.
The natural follow through.  As I see it Black has a few options here.  He can take my knight (Nxd4) Move the queen up to d7 (my favorite) or what he wound up doing.

This move I think is a mistake.  It allows me to add some pressure onto him by my next move.  It does appear to be a good move on the surface and gave me some pause.  If I take his bishop on b7 with my own he can retake with his knight and while that puts his knight in a bad position it doesn't give me a lot of attack options.  I still need to see if I can get him to take my bishop so I can move my e pawn and get my rook into the game.
Putting pressure on his knight and continuing my development.
Success so far let's see where this takes us.

Retaking is imperative here but it also allows me to bring my rook into the game.  As his knight is still under attack he has to either move it or defend it.    The best move from this position I think is the one he made.
Not only does this give his knight a good-looking post it also simultaneously attacks my bishop and b pawn.
To defend the b pawn and move my bishop out of harm's way.  So far we are even on exchanges but I have a significant attack angle on his king almost no matter what he does.

This move surprised me a little bit as I anticipated him bringing his knight to the same square to allow him to move closer to castling and safety for his king.  However the post of his d pawn looks to be helpful.
Building the pressure.

Black's best move here is to move his king to f8.  It will complicate his position as he will have to find an alternative way to get his rook into the game but this move opens him up to a nasty attack which I did not use because of tunnel vision.
Time to wade in to dislodge the queen give my knight a nice post and also add additional pressure on the knight.

This is a blunder on my part.  I had tunnel vision and didn't analyze as well as I should have.  I was thinking that he would try to castle kingside giving me significant advantage against his knight which would come out to give his king.  The proper play here is to bring the f pawn into the fray with f4.


15.	f4	Ne7
16.	fxe5	dxe5
17.	Bxe5	O-O
18.	Bxf6	Nxc6
19.	dxc6	Qxd1
20.	Rxd1	gxf6
21.	Rd7	Rac8
22.	Nd2	Rfe8
23.	Nf3
The computer rates this move as an inaccuracy saying it is better to castle queenside.  I don't know how I feel about a queenside castle here as his pawn structure is wide open.
Giving a chance for a castle or other escape.

Adding pressure to his knight.  If he castles then I get his knight for free.  Also bringing the queen to the e2 square will allow me to bring my rook over for a triple battery if and when I can my knight into the game.
This is a great response from Black and I congratulated him in game.  This move gives him the space to bring his king up to f7 and relieve the pressure on his knight.

I toyed around with the idea of Re6 for some time here but ultimately decided against it.  I like the extra protection of the f pawn and once he brings his king up it could complicate matters for me down the road with protection.  Better to avoid all of that and make a tactical retreat for the time being.
Giving his knight a chance to get back into the game.
This move lets me protect my d pawn a little longer since it was unprotected at this point.  Bringing the knight out is no good as b4 would dislodge it.
This move allows me two options.  One is a retake with my queen or bringing my knight out first.
This move finishes my piece development and allows me to get the rook into the game.  It also provides some extra protection to my d pawn which is in danger.
I am uncertain if this is the best rook to bring into the battery role for the d half file but will defer to allanchessw's analysis on the matter.
Regaining the 1 pawn advantage and threatening a discovered check on his king.
I have a few options here but ultimately decided that a queen trade was not as advantageous as a pawn grab with check would be.
Natural response.

I have two options and this one is the better of the two in my opinion.  I need to protect the d1 square since my king is subject to a back-rank mate if I do not.  Moving to the c2 square is preferred since it allows my rook on the a1 square to move more freely.
I thought black might try Rc8 which would force me to move Qe2 however he went for the triple battery.
Forced to allow my king an escape route.
Offering a queen exchange.  I'm not ready for this route especially since his h pawn is open.
The computer rates this as a blunder.  I have no real option but to move my a rook to e1 and that creates a powerful combination to assault black's king.
Now I am at a crossroads.  Black's king is exposed and surrounded by powerful pieces.  My mating radar was going off big time and I knew there was a winning combination there.

This move is a blunder on my part.  I thought long and hard about it and thought I had every possible response mapped but I didn't count on one.  Luckily Black did not see the ideal response either as it would have negated my move.  I was actually really pumped about this sequence until I saw the computer analysis.  

Discounting Qd5 black is going down almost no matter what he plays here.  The question becomes what pieces does he want left at the end.

The ideal sequence is 
29.	Qh5+		g6
30.	Re7+!!	Rxe7
31.	Qh7+		Kf8
32.	Qxe7+	Kg8
33.	Qxd8+	Kg7
34.	Re7+		Qf7
35.	Rxf7+	Kxf7
36.	Qd7+		Kg8
37.	Qe6+		Kg7
38.	Qe7+		Kh6
39.	Qxf6
Discounting the Qd5 ideal response this is the only move on black's part that didn't end in either mate or serious loss of points/pieces.
Any other move is mate.

And now black has to decide do I block with the queen and go down the path of 
32.	Qh8+		Qg8
33.	Rxe8+	Kxe8
34.	Qxg8+	Ke7
35.	Qxg6	

or do I want to lose both of my rooks with 
32.	Qh8+		Kf7
33.	Qxe8+	Kg7
34.	Qxd7+	

Here black resigned.  I consider allanchessw a tremendous player and will look forward to future matches with him.
White opens e4.
Black counters with c5
White advances a pawn to b3 on the queen side to open up his bishop.
I bring out my kings knight to f6 to pressure the middle white pawn on e4.
White brings out the queens knight to c3 to protect the middle e4 pawn.
I bring up my black pawn to d5 to add pressure to the middle pawn in e4.
White passes my black pawn and puts pressure on black knight on f6.
I move up my knight to e4.
White knight takes my pawn in d5.
I take the knight in d5 with my queen. That was a blunder I guess. I was not sure if it was a trap of some kind. Time will tell.
White brings out the bishop to c4 and pressures my queen in d5.
I push up my black queen to d4 pressuring the rook in a1 and same time his King and pawn on f2 which has pressure from my knight.
White queen  protects her King by moving to e2.
I take the rook in a1 with my queen. I now have pressure on his bishop on c1.
White brings back the queen to d1 to protect the bishop in c1.
I bring my black queen back to center on d4 to where he first countered with his queen to e2. This time I think he decides to do something different. Watch what happens next.
White brings out the kings side knight to f3 a strong position to pressure my queen on d4. His next move would be to castle O-O.

I had to move my queen out of harms way and I looked  at the pawn on f2 and see that its protected by my knight on e4. If I used my knight to take his pawn in f2 I would pressure his kings rook and queen at the same time. I had a better move and put him in checkmate with my queen to his pawn in f2 for check mate. This was my 5th win. This was done in 9 moves over a 12 day time period.
I start with one of my favourite defences.
Better would've been Bf4.
As white I'd prefer c3 followed by Nd2 but I'd prefer no exchange variation in the caro kann at all!
Prevents Bf4.
At this point I was thinking about supporting my d pawn to play d4 followed by Rxc2.
This part would just be boring with each move being one to avoid loss on timeout.
Blockades whites advance. My LSb will now be very powerful.
B
This is now completely winning for me after a4 since I have activity on the c file and my LSb is worth a lot.
Attacks the knight.
The game is over now. I will have an advantage of 3 pawns.
Resigns.

This game was played in the USA championship (1963-64) where Bobby Fischer-at the ago of 20-has won by winning all of his matcheswhich is a unique performance in the history of chess. The writer never annotates the opening-parts so the quote starts here:)
"The opening is Pirc defense. For blackthis last move gave the most opportunities."
"12.exf5 would give black chanses to fight back with 12...e4"
"Fischer said that he was thinking about 13.Qxe5 Hg4 14.Qxg7!? Kxg7 moves which where a lot promising."
"Black is planning the move f5 which would free his position."
"This blocks blacks planned move 15...f5 because 16.Bh6 starts a strong attack."
"Againblocks f5 move."
"16...c5 would have been a better defense."
"Threatening 18.Bxd4 exd4 19.e5"
"Tricky move but not good. The best would have been 17...Ne6"

"19.e5 wouldn't be good because of 19...f5. This is what black was waiting for but white's move was like lightning out of the blue. On the dinner held at the end of the competition a cake was served having this position in it."
"If 19...dxc3 than 20.e5 h6 20.Rxh6+ Kg8 22.Rh8+ Bxh8 23.Qh7#

"Black resigned herehis position is hopeless."
End of the quote. The annotation might be a bit boring but consider it my weak translation:) In hungarian it would sound a bit better but there is no big difference I think
The goal was to show you an nice matchhope you like it. Feel free to rate and comment. :)

An unusual variation of the Ruy Lopez the Exchange Variation is infrequently used but is quite sound. In the words of Dr. Reuben Fine "White heads straight for the end game. Every time a piece is exchanged he is one step nearer his goal... Theoretically there seems to be little wrong with White's plan which is why the line can be held quiescent but never made to disappear completely." All the games in the tournanment begin with this position.

Of course since I'm Black I *don't* want to exchange pieces at least until the Pawn structure is more favorably disposed towards me in an end game. However I do wish to drive the Knight from the fine square KB5.
Pressuring the White KP.
Clearing the open file for my Rook.
I must guard the Knight.
Now I centralize it. i realize at least one minor piece will be exchanged but I have little choice.
Now i have 2 B's against 2 Knights so if the heavy pieces are exchanged and I end up in an end game that should compensate for my disadvantage in Pawn position.
Focusing my fire on the advanced KP.
Now I can create a Pawn weakness for White...
...which I do with this exchange.
White trades down.
I look to exploit White's weakened Q-side Pawns.
The obvious threat which for some reason...
...White doesn't respond to. I was expecting 22 R-QB1 to preserve material equality.
Time to activate...
...and centralize my King.
Looking to weaken White's K-side Pawns as well.
White chooses to exchange.
I bypass the Pawn push.
I take immediate adavantage of White's tactical error. White resigns as the Knight must fall. An abrupt ending to what looked like it was going to be a long strategic end game.
Another tournament game for me this comes while my rating is at its lowest range for some considerable time. This game however was over in only 6 moves.
Tournament start position Bird opening From Gambit.
Nothing much wrong with this move it's been a common one in the tournament.
A bit of me thinks this is is a strange move and I have had mixed success with it in the tournament.

For me this move was a bit of an experiment previous efforts had mostly revolved around Bxd6 but here I stuck with the old adage of getting knights out before bishops. The gameknot database seems to indicate this as promising too.

From my perspective I was starting to get ideas about a possible Ne4 and Qh4 early attack trying to take advantage of the e1-h4 open diagonal
No real alternative here that I could see and I would love to get my queen to g3
This is the sort of normal developing move that with the benefit of hindsight looks quite weak. I'm not sure what would be better perhaps e3 or Nc2

Looking to tease the h pawn forward if that doesn't work then the e pawn is still pinned to the queen and I have Bd6 threatening a bishop sac on h2 perhaps Bd6 would have been the better move I'm still not entirely sure.
This is the losing move for white.

White resigned due to Kd2 Ne4#

Many thanks for reading please comment.
Entering the Grunfeld Defense. More suiting my style of late is 3.Nf3 making sure Black gets in the King's Indian Defense.
Bg7 is more common but this is an active response that works well.
Bc4 is just as good but I take after the old masters who said to develop the knights before bishops :)
I like this direct response but Rb1 is most played.
Usually you don't want to bring out your queen this early on and this far but it has a strong purpose on a5.
I have a pawn majority in the center but it is under attack at the moment. I also have a semi-open file that I need to find out how I can put it to use.
Without queens on the board and the lack of black's development I don't have to worry so much about attacks against my king.
Opening a line for my bishop and gaining more space.
Nb4 leaves a strong possibility of the knight being trapped.
Restricting counterplay from black.
A key moment in the game: advance my pawns and possibly overextend or ease into the crux of black's counterplay. Bxe7 is met simply with Re8 and a fork comes on e4.
I decide to have faith in my pawns.
I've won a pawn but can I hold on to it?
A key move from black the creates the draw. Bd4 and black will slowly win the pawns on e7 and e5 with the advance of the king.

I offered a draw based on us both having dark/light square bishops and equal material without any sight of an endgame advantage for each side. The pawn on e7 falls in no time after Kf7 and Rc7. A solid game from both players. Black seemed to play with more purpose but came up short on an advantage.
This is one of my longer games with a very interesting endgame.  I go down a pawn early and must fight to attempt to equalize after losing the initiative...

At this point I considered recapturing with my bishop as opposed to my queen.  The advantage of a bishop recapture keeps my queen from being overexposed.  The advantage of a queen recapture is a solid central location for the queen.  Both the game database and post game analysis recommend capturing with the queen.  My instinct was to recapture with the bishop.  If anybody can explain whether or not the queen recapture is indeed superior I would appreciate it.
Attempting to chase the knight away from the king's defense...
Now I am down a pawn and his queen is centrally located.  I did not want to exchange queens as I had a pawn attack formed on the kingside and I wanted to keep my strongest piece for attack options.
Supporting a potential g-pawn advance.
Queenside charge from black.
I am trading a piece for two pawns and eliminating blacks brutal pawn center.
If 24...Rxf2 then 25. Rd8+ leads to mate.
Offering the queen which perhaps should have been traded earlier...
Black trades with the tempo of a Rook activation.
And here is where the endgame (in my opinion) begins.  I am the equivalent of a pawn down but I have two passed pawns on the queenside.  Can I take advantage of this fact?
Blocking the a-pawn advance.
The king's only move is c7.  If he moves there then white Ka7 will ensure the b-pawn promotion.  He has the option of advancing his g-pawn or h-pawn however neither of those options are very good...
If instead 52...g6 then 53. Kb6 and either 53...Kc7 give white a queen from the b-pawn or 53...h6 gives white a passed pawn on the h-file with a queen to quickly follow.
And here we see a classic example of Zugzwang.  Black's only legal move is 54...Kc7
Which allows...
And black resigned.

A "Walking The Walk" Club game.  Thank you to brigadecommander for playing.  My assessment is that questionable moves by white at 15 and 16 and then unwisely forging ahead with a bad plan at 17 and 18 clinched the loss.
effectively a queen's pawn game.
trying to reduce black's arsenal while bringing my bishop and f-pawn more in to play.

perhaps 8. h3 and 12. f4 have invited a side attack on the white king's position.  at this point even though neither king is facing a threat it is easy to see that black's king is much more safely situated than white's. will this be a key factor in the outcome of the game?
couldn't commit to a plan to remove black's d-pawn and so played c3 to hinder her knight.  but since I went on to c4 soon this move wasted time.

noticing that white is very porous here while black has retained all of her pawns' potential keeping them well fed and housed and in reserve.  perhaps white can proceed with a plan that plays off an early space advantage.  or perhaps black will break apart white's overly advanced pawns and gain control of valuable central real estate.

an ok move by itself BUT it may be the start of my problems a few moves later.  I wanted to remove black's central pawn.  but if the c-pawn was going to be involved this move has the problem of ...Nb4.

almost played Nb3 (probably a better choice ...possibly wins bishop with Nc5).  this a3 is part of white's overcommitment to the poor plan of c4 (and it's failure to take in to account the problems of putting the knight on c4).

at this point I had been thinking black attacks c4 twice.  but c4 is really attacked three times because the black bishop can go to b5 after BxP (if NxP and NxN now).  a bit tricky but not something I should have missed.  Had I played 15. Qc1 instead of Qc2 (or not played 18. NxN coming up) this problem would have been avoided.
white should have taken his lumps and left the black knight alone.  the idea that the white e-pawn could advance once black's d-pawn was removed played in to the irrational...
...NxN which seals the game.  or perhaps commenters will find a way to proceed even once 18. Nxc4 has been played.
BxP.
Bb5 as expected (too late).  I dislike black's central pawn more and more and it is now causing me more trouble than before. so...
...BxP.  allows a white rook to move to c1 in time to prevent too much damage and may enable white to have a strong pawn presence in the center.
NxB.

prevents white from having to defend knight on c4 with heavy pieces.  BUT misses that it gives black a fork of white's queen and rook after BxN & QxB.  had seen that but rushed a bit and will now pay.  thought about proposing a bending of the club rulez here ...resign and start a new game.  but went a head with some very dull mechanical play.
BxP.  earlier I thought I could respond to this with Rd1.  worked out that that was a poor option.  I did not want to be w/o my knight but...
went ahead with NxB.  had I seen ANY decent other options for the knight I would have kept it in the game.  unhappily its best use seemed to be to remove the bishop.

Hi everyone!

Here is the second instance where I thought I had a decent mating attack going against my opponent.  I intended to go right for the jugular here which is fairly rare for jstevens1!  However in doing so I overlooked a tactical shot.  I thought I could get out of it but then a knight move from my opponent gave me grim confirmation that I would remain a piece light.  Again after that I waved the white flag.  So how did this happen?  Well read on.  Gameknot analysis link to follow:- http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=17067335&fb=1&rnd=0.3711907782109783

14..... Qh4+ - ..... for Glenda!  This is not where Glenda usually resides sadly this unfamiliar territory proves to be her undoing later on.
17. Nxf3 - I sacrifice a pawn to denude the WK and launch a direct mating attack.  Unfortunately Glenda needs a little assistance in order to do this.
18. .... Ngf6 - and so I bring a knight into play.
20. ...... Bf6 - threatening to come into h4 but here comes the tactical shot.
21. Ne5 - first up a discovered attack.
22. Nxd7+ - as per my earlier note the piece-winning combo is on due to the unfortunate placement of Henry.

24. ...... Rd8 - the knight is trapped but .....
25. .... f5 - my passer on f7 moves up two squares to defend it and the d7 knight is still trapped but .....

26. Ne2 - ... a white knight move seals my fate.  Fou Lenoir will be exchanged off and I will remain a piece down.  As I said in the intro time to write this game off as I have no counterplay whatsoever.  I think I had better look at some tactical puzzles to try and get my rating back into the 1800s!  Joanne

Kh1 was the only move that would have saved me in this position.  That is because he has just spotted a mating sequence against me.  If I had taken my time I would have seen this threat.

I do not why I made this move but it does not matter where I move at this point.  As I had mentioned earlier he has an inevitable mating pattern against me and will mate me with Qg2# (forced mate) after he plays Qg4+.  Therefore I resign after he checks me with Qg4.

I did not learn but will remember an important lesson from this game combined with other games in December and mentoring games.  First chess is not an entertaining game.  Instead it is much more serious then that so it is a good idea to study the board and take time to analyze the positions before you make a move.  It will also help to alleviate boredom if you annotate games use analyze the board flip and/or game notes in the process.  There are also some occasions where one must tolerate boredom to play well and Jack Stockel agrees with this assessment.  After these rushed games I take chess as serious as my hardest college courses (Precalculus and Inorganic Chemistry 1).  Second when you move too quickly your mind cannot absorb the information so you do not learn from your mistakes.  After all when you rush you are not being careful.  When you are not careful you get into trouble.

Gambits can make for some exicting chess and this game is a good example of that. However the trouble with gambits is that they are generally wrong and will lead to death. The keys to refuting a gambit lay in accepting it once but not twice. This means if your opponent offers a freebie once take it but refuse it the second freebie. Otherwise you can be caught being to greedly. The other key of refuting a gamibt is to play principled chess that follows the rules. I.E develop your pieces control the centre and ensure your king's safety. Finally if your opponent offers you a freebie take it and dare them to prove that going behind in material for nothing is worth it.

?? you should only gambit a piece if you have a clear bullet proof checkmate. This is not the case here since after 4. ...Nxe4 all black has to do is ride the wave and come out with a clear material advantage. A better strategy is to complete your development and solidify your center before attacking. If you want a good alternative to this move then 4. d4 dxd4 5. Nxd4 is slightly better for white. 

What are good gambits and bad gambits? Good gambits are essentially a trade off between material balance and one other tangible advantage such as rapid development and open lines to the king If none of these conditions exicts as it did doesn't in this case then it is bad.
Having played the gambit the gambiteer must play activity or risk being out gunned latter on.

However 11. ...0-0 helps black by encouraging him to do what he wanted to anyway which is to castle. These positions are very difficult to play because white has to play assertively due to the material imbalance and extremely overextended center. Therefore white can easily run into the risk of overplaying and collapsing like a deck of cards. I would caution against facilitating your enemies plans while ingoring your weaknesses. There are several ways that you can prevent your opponent from doing what they want but one of the best ways is distractions. An example of this is that white can force black into making a long term weakness with 11. e6 Bxe6 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. Qh5! black is right to attack the knight because white can not allow holes to appear in front of his king. the threat is Bxn.

It looks as though b7 is a free catch but you would be wrong. The real problem for white is his weakness on the dark squares. If you look at the positions of the kings you may notice that white is actually more open. Matter of fact he is sitting on the c1-h6 diagonal which is controled by black. Not only that 13. Bxb7 opens up another line to the king via the b file. the rule is to keep all roads to your king closed. But the question is how does white do that? The answer is 13. Ne4 which deals with the threat of Bxn and covers the g5 square from back door checks. It is difficult to resist the attack at all costs plan since it is often flashy and fun. However the "guns ablaze" strategy can only work in overwelming odds situations and since chess starts out with both players being equal then "guns blazing" rarely works. It takes experience to understand when it is time to let go of the chances for winning and embrace a draw as an acceptable result.

The opening begins with 1.d4 d5.  It is also possible to reach it by 1.c3 d5 2.d4.
Black continues like white taking control of part of the center.
This move may seem a bit unusual as it blocks the c3 square and does not develop any pieces.  However it creates a solid center for white and takes black out of the opening book.

This move is a normal move in position because black wants to develop his white squared bishop before playing e6.  The problem is that black is not quite sure where the bishop is best placed and it may spend extra tempi moving to a better square.
I believe I am the developer of this move.  The idea is to force the bishop to move again while losing time.
There is no reason black should decline the gambit because if he is going to lose tempi he might as well have a pawn for them.
This move is much better than f3 or h3 because it develops a piece while forcing black to do something about his g4 bishop.

This probably is not the best move in the position as white can exchange bishops and play Qb3 targeting the weak b7 pawn.  Alternative lines include: 4...Bxh3 5.Nxh3 Nf6 6.Qb3 Qc8 7.Bf4! (if 7...Qxh3?? 8.Qxb7 Qg2 9.Rf1+-) with an interesting game and 4...Nf6 5.Qb3 which may transpose to the Bxh3 line.
